{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01DKgBHN9YrXFXf1E3BB54Fe","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior in the Node.js plugin loader issue.\n\n**Behavior 1**: A plugin whose manifest is missing a required field is rejected before any code from that plugin is executed.\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This is about manifest validation logic — parsing JSON and checking required fields. This is pure logic that can be tested at Unit level.\n- REAL-INFRA: No OS/network dependency needed for the validation logic itself. However, reading manifest.json from a directory is filesystem I/O. We could test the validation function in isolation with a mock manifest object, OR test the loader reading from actual files. The key failure here is \"rejected before any code executed\" — we need to verify that the validation happens before module import. \n- MOCK-HIDE: To verify the \"before any code is executed\" constraint, I need to confirm that the plugin's entry module is never imported when validation fails. Testing the validation function alone won't prove this ordering, so I need at least an Integration test that shows rejection prevents the module from being loaded.\n- LLM-DEP: No.\n- MULTI-STEP: No.\n\nTo verify that manifest validation happens before the module import step, I could set up a plugin with an invalid manifest that has a side effect in its entry module, run the loader, and check that the side effect never occurs. This requires wiring together the actual manifest reading, validation, and import sequence—that's Integration level.\n\nFor the dependency ordering behavior, I need to test both the topological sort algorithm and the actual hook invocation sequence. While the ordering algorithm itself could be Unit tested, verifying that hooks fire in the correct order requires the full loader wiring with real manifest reading from the filesystem.\n\nOn the cycle detection behavior, there are really two concerns: detecting the cycle itself (which could be Unit tested) and ensuring neither plugin loads as a result. The \"loads neither\" part means verifying no hooks are called, which requires Integration testing to confirm the loader's actual response to cycles.\n\nFor the onLoad hook timing, the test needs to verify the actual sequence of module import followed by hook invocation. Mocking the import would defeat the purpose since that's the mechanism being tested. This is Integration — it's about how the loader wires these two operations together, and it needs real filesystem access so the plugin files can actually be imported.\n\nWhen a plugin's onLoad hook throws an error, the loader should continue initializing unrelated plugins. This is also Integration because it requires multiple plugins running together with one failing, and the loader's error recovery behavior only makes sense when the full system is operating. Mocking individual hooks would miss the interaction between error handling and the continued loading of other plugins.\n\nBoth behaviors are clearly Integration level. Now I'm reconsidering whether Behavior 1 — the manifest validation — might actually be testable at Unit level since the validation logic itself is just parsing and checking a data structure. theoretically be tested at Unit level (just test the validation function with a fake manifest object). But the \"before any code is executed\" part requires verifying the ordering, which is Integration. So minimum is Integration.\n\nFor behaviors 2-5, they all require multiple modules working together with filesystem and actual plugin loading. Integration seems right.\n\nNone of these require real LLM, real HTTP, or real external APIs. They're all about local filesystem I/O and module loading, so System is not needed (no subprocess, OS behavior beyond filesystem, or real HTTP).\n\nLet me re-examine each behavior. B1 needs Integration to verify the ordering constraint. B2 requires Integration to confirm hook invocation follows dependency order. B3 needs Integration to verify cycle detection prevents loading. B4 fundamentally requires Integration because I need actual module loading to verify the import-before-hook sequence. B5 needs Integration to test multiple plugins where one fails and others continue.\n\nAll of these are Integration-level tests. Now I'm assigning probability distributions for each behavior, starting with B1 where Unit is low since validation alone doesn't capture the ordering requirement, Integration is high at 0.80 since that's where the real constraint lives, and System/Agentic/Workflow are minimal. For B2 through B5, I'm following similar patterns based on how much cross-module coordination each behavior requires. I'm realizing that Unit tests alone can't verify the behavioral constraints here—they'd only test the validation function in isolation, not whether the loader actually prevents module imports or hook execution. Integration tests are necessary to confirm the loader's end-to-end behavior, so I'm confident all five behaviors require Integration-level testing.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9572,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9572},"output_tokens":6,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9334d49d-96fe-412a-81da-d2e51ead1b57","uuid":"6b904431-a74f-42be-9314-123ad8c774a5"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01DKgBHN9YrXFXf1E3BB54Fe","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01AaacKoqHqdeNNi7xeZBefT","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"A plugin whose manifest is missing a required field is rejected before any code from that plugin is executed.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The validation logic itself is Unit-testable in isolation, but the critical constraint — 'before any code is executed' — is a sequencing guarantee between the manifest validator and the module importer. A Unit test of the validation function cannot verify that the loader refrains from calling require/import on a rejected plugin. MOCK-HIDE: If we mock the module loader, we always pass trivially; a spy on require/import calls must be verified against actual loader wiring reading real manifests from a temp directory. The failure lives at the hand-off between validator and importer, making Integration the minimum.","test_description":"Create a temp plugin directory with one plugin whose manifest.json omits a required field (e.g., 'name') and one valid plugin. Instrument the invalid plugin's entry module with a side-effect (e.g., writes to a shared flag). Run the loader against the directory. Assert: (a) the loader emits a validation error for the invalid plugin, and (b) the side-effect flag is never set, proving the entry module was never imported.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.8,"System":0.06,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When plugin A declares a dependency on plugin B, plugin B's onLoad hook is called before plugin A's.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The topological sort algorithm is Unit-testable, but the behavior's failure mode is not in the sorting — it's in whether the sorted order is actually used when invoking onLoad hooks. A bug that sorts correctly but invokes in declaration order would pass a Unit test. MOCK-HIDE: Mocking the hook invocations and asserting call order still requires the real dependency resolution pipeline to feed the correct order into the invoker. We need manifest files on disk, the resolver, and the hook dispatcher all wired together to see a real failure. Integration is the minimum level.","test_description":"Create a temp directory with two plugins: plugin B (no dependencies) and plugin A (declares dependency on B). Each plugin's onLoad records its name to a shared invocation log. Run the loader. Assert the log shows B before A.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.15,"Integration":0.76,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When two plugins each declare a dependency on the other, the loader reports the cycle and loads neither.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: Cycle detection (e.g., DFS on a dependency graph) is Unit-testable in isolation. However, 'loads neither' is a separate guarantee — the loader must not invoke onLoad or import entry modules for either plugin. That constraint spans the cycle detector, the load gating logic, and the hook dispatcher. A Unit test of the detection function cannot verify that the dispatch layer respects the cycle gate. REJECTION-GATE: I considered Unit for the detection algorithm but it cannot falsify 'loads neither', so Integration stands.","test_description":"Create a temp directory with plugin X declaring dependency on Y, and plugin Y declaring dependency on X. Instrument both entry modules with side-effect flags. Run the loader. Assert: (a) the loader emits a cycle error naming both plugins, and (b) neither side-effect flag was set and neither onLoad was called.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.18,"Integration":0.72,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.03}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"A plugin's onLoad hook is only invoked after the plugin's entry module has been imported and executed.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: This behavior is entirely about the sequencing between two loader phases: module import/execution and hook dispatch. There is no standalone function to Unit test — the failure only manifests when the phases are wired in the wrong order, or when onLoad is called on a module object that hasn't been initialized yet. MOCK-HIDE: Mocking require/import defeats the test — we need a real module file that sets state during its top-level execution, and the onLoad must observe that state. The failure boundary is between the importer and the hook caller. Integration is the minimum.","test_description":"Create a plugin whose entry module sets a module-level flag (e.g., `module.exports.ready = true`) during execution. The plugin's onLoad reads that flag and throws if it is not set. Run the loader. Assert onLoad completes without error, confirming the entry module was fully executed before the hook was called.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.85,"System":0.06,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When a plugin throws an error during its onLoad hook, the loader continues initializing the remaining plugins that do not depend on it.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: Error recovery across multiple plugins is inherently a multi-module concern — the error handler, the load sequencer, and all subsequent plugin hooks must interact correctly. A Unit test can verify that a single try/catch swallows an error, but it cannot verify that the loader resumes the remaining queue and invokes subsequent hooks. MOCK-HIDE: Mocking subsequent plugins' hooks makes the test trivially pass regardless of whether the loader actually continues; real plugin files with observable side-effects are needed to detect a premature abort. Integration is the minimum.","test_description":"Create three plugins with no inter-dependencies: plugin A (onLoad succeeds), plugin B (onLoad throws), plugin C (onLoad records to a log). Run the loader. Assert: (a) the loader reports an error for plugin B, and (b) plugin C's onLoad was called and its log entry is present, proving the loader continued past the failure.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.06,"Integration":0.84,"System":0.06,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.02}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9572,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9572},"output_tokens":6,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9334d49d-96fe-412a-81da-d2e51ead1b57","uuid":"b0ae9c46-5b6a-4057-a228-4a665037e71b"}
